One of the primary drivers of inequality in urban communities is access to and attainment of various levels of education. The Bay Area is no different, and specifically Santa Clara county sees significant racial inequities among its over-25 population (hereafter referred to as the adult population) with regard to level of education attainment, according to the 2019 American Communities Survey (ACS 2019). While the adult population of Santa Clara County is overwhelmingly represented in the Bachelors Degree or Higher Category, (Fig 1) the distribution of this attainment level is not equal to the baseline racial distribution. In Figure 2, we can see that the Asian racial group is disproportionately highly represented in the category of those holding a Bachelors Degree or Higher, while all other sampled racial groups are underrepresented in this category. At the next 2 levels of education attainment; Some college or associates degree and High school graduate, the White population becomes over represented. At the lowest level, Less than high school diploma, both White and Asian populations are significantly underrepresented, while the Some other race category is extremely over represented. The general story that the data tells is that, in mid-level attainment categories, the adult White population is over represented, in high-level attainment categories, the adult Asian population is over represented, and the adult Other population suffer from over representation at the lowest attainment level.

In Part 2 of this analysis, we look at education attainment levels by ethnicity according to the Census. It is important to note a significant assumption of this data. We have here visualized by White, Not Latinx, Latinx, and Not White, Not Latinx. This is constructed from the Census ACS data, which collects data based on individuals who identify as Hispanic. Therefore we are making the assumption that those who identify as Hispanic would also identify as Latinx. We are also not capturing those that may identify as any other combination of Latinx and another race or ethnicity (Black Latinx, White Latinx, Alaska Native Latinx, etc.). The data, as we have collected it, presents a very clear and striking picture about the representation of Latinx community members with regard to education in Santa Clara County. It is particularly noticeable how strongly over represented the Latinx community is in the category of adults aged 25 years or older who have less than a high school diploma. In fact, 56% of the adult population without a high school diploma identifies as Latinx, while only 21% of the adult population identifies as Latinx. The Latinx community is over represented by a factor of 2.67 in the Bay Area with regard to the attainment of a High School Diploma. The over representation of the Latinx community continues up to those adults that have graduated high school (factor of 1.86), as well as those with some college or an associates degree (factor of 1.19). The story reverses, however, when looking at adults over 25 in the Bay area with a bachelors degree or higher. In this case, the Latinx community is under represented drastically, by a factor of 3.0. As we move up in levels of educational attainment, the equity of the Latinx community representation decreases significantly from over representation in the lowest levels to under representation in the highest levels tracked. The opposite story is true for both the White, Not Latinx and Not White, Not Latinx populations, which become over represented at higher educational attainment levels.

The overall conclusion of this data is therefore that there is absolutely both a racial and ethnic disparity in the level of educational attainment in the Bay Area of California, with minorities generally being under represented at higher attainment levels, especially the level of a Bachelors Degree or higher
